description.narrative:
CRTA confirms that the project implementation continues in accordance with theactivity plan and the budget, and in line with the grant agreement. COVID19 situationcaused mainly reschedluing and move to online activities, but no shift of the programme focus. There are no major delays in the programme and no considerable deviations in plans. Sida welcomes our cooperation partner to adapt to reality. In the Embassy dialog with CRTA there are no issues that remain unaddressed. CRTA displays openess and transparency in dialog, and capacity and willingness to continuously strengthen the organisation.
Some examples of reported results in the reporting period:
- Provided full support (training, technical and grant support) to a total of seven local civil society organisations;
- Launched and broadly disseminated the CRTA’s “18+” documentary series focusing on generation of the first-time voters who were allowed to vote in the 2020 parliamentary elections:
- Established strategy scope and messaging for the second wave of the CRTA’s communications and outreach campaign “Standing by Democracy” aiming broad mobilisation of citizens in action to defend democracy;
- Strengthened and maintained engagement of network members within CRTA’s election observation mission proved of crucial importance for the assessment of regularity and quality of the campaign around parliamentary elections 2020 and ensuring the evidence for CRTA’s adequate reaction and employment of legal mechanisms in response to identified electoral breaches on the ground;
With results of continued investment in communication and outreach capacities and skills of both CRTA and its civil society partners towards strengthening their effectiveness and impact in building the lasting demand for democracy, this Programme’s theory of change remains highly relevant.
